.TH "ANIMATION.COMMITSTYLES" "3JS" "November 7, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Animation.commitStyles \- Animation: commitStyles() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] method of the Web Animations API\(cqs
\f[CR]Animation\f[R] interface writes the computed values of the
animation\(cqs current styles into its target element\(cqs
\f[CR]style\f[R] attribute.
.PP
It is primarily used to write the styles for the final state of an
animation into the target element, so that the styling persists after
the animation ends.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
commitStyles()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] method is primarily used to write the
computed values for the final state of an animation into the target
element\(cqs \f[CR]style\f[R] attribute, so that the styling persists
after the animation ends.
This can be done when the animation has finished (that is, the
\f[CR]Animation\f[R] object\(cqs \f[CR]finished\f[R] property has
resolved).
.SS \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] alongside fill mode
On older browsers, you must specify the \f[CR]fill\f[R] mode in order to
be able to commit the styles to the element \f[I]after\f[R] the
animation has finished.
.PP
The code below shows how you can animate an element named
\f[CR]animatedElement\f[R], setting \f[CR]fill: \(dqforwards\(dq\f[R] to
persist the animation styles after it finishes.
Once the animation is finished we commit the styles to the element with
\f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Start the animation\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] animation = animatedElement.animate(
  { transform: \(dqtranslate(100px)\(dq },
  { duration: 500, fill: \(dqforwards\(dq },
);

\f[I]// Wait for the animation to finish\f[R]
\f[B]await\f[R] animation.finished;
\f[I]// Commit animation state to he animatedElement style attribute\f[R]
animation.commitStyles();
\f[I]// Cancel the animation\f[R]
animation.cancel();
.EE
.PP
As \f[CR]fill\f[R] persists the animation indefinitely, once we\(cqve
committed the styles, we cancel the animation.
.PP
Note that the same effect could be achieved with \f[CR]fill\f[R] alone,
but \c
.UR https://drafts.csswg.org/web-animations-1/#fill-behavior
using indefinitely filling animations is discouraged
.UE \c
\&.
Animations take precedence over all static styles, so an indefinite
filling animation can prevent the target element from ever being styled
normally.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] You might also avoid having to explicitly save the final
state by setting them as the element initial styles and animating to the
final styles.
.RE
.SS \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] without setting fill mode
In newer browsers you do not need to set the \f[CR]fill\f[R] mode (see
the browser compatibility table for specific versions).
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] There is no way to feature check for this new behavior.
For now most code should continue to set \f[CR]fill\f[R] as shown in the
previous section.
.RE
.PP
The code below shows how you can animate an element named
\f[CR]animatedElement\f[R], wait on the animation to complete using the
\f[CR]finished\f[R] property, and then commit the styles to the element
with \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R].
Because we\(cqre not setting \f[CR]fill\f[R] we don\(cqt have to cancel
the animation afterwards.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Start the animation\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] animation = animatedElement.animate(
  { transform: \(dqtranslate(100px)\(dq },
  { duration: 500 },
);

\f[I]// Wait for the animation to finish\f[R]
\f[B]await\f[R] animation.finished;

\f[I]// Commit animation state to the animatedElement style attribute\f[R]
animation.commitStyles();
.EE
.PP
\f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] works even if the animation has been
automatically removed.
After the element\(cqs styles have been committed they can be modified
and replaced as normal.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Animation with and without using fill
This example demonstrates how you can use \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] to
save the computed styles at the end of the animation, both with and
without using \f[CR]fill\f[R].
It also provides an example of what happens if neither
\f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] or \f[CR]fill\f[R] are used, for comparison.
.PP
The example first displays two buttons labelled \(lqcommitStyles()
only\(rq and \(lqcommitStyles() with fill\(rq.
Both buttons animate when you click them, and both buttons call
\f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] to persist the final state of the animation.
The difference is that \(lqcommitStyles() only\(rq does not specify
\f[CR]fill: \(dqforwards\(dq\f[R] to persist the animation\(cqs final
state.
On browsers that don\(cqt match the current specification the final
state may not be captured.
.PP
The code then displays a button \(lqNo commitStyles() or fill\(rq that
can be used for comparison, and a \(lqReset\(rq button.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]button\f[R] class=\(dqcommit\-styles\(dq>commitStyles() only</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]button\f[R] class=\(dqcommit\-with\-fill\(dq>commitStyles() with fill</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]button\f[R] class=\(dqno\-commit\-or\-fill\(dq>No commitStyles() or fill</\f[B]button\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
This code defines a click handler for the \(lqcommitStyles() only\(rq
button.
This animates the button to move right or left when it is clicked.
Note that \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] is called immediately after the
animation is finished.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] offset1 = 0;

\f[B]const\f[R] commitStyles = document.querySelector(\(dq.commit\-styles\(dq);

commitStyles.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, \f[B]async\f[R] (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Start the animation\f[R]
  offset1 = 100 \- offset1;
  \f[B]const\f[R] animation = commitStyles.animate(
    { transform: \(gatranslate(${offset1}px)\(ga },
    { duration: 500 },
  );

  \f[I]// Wait for the animation to finish\f[R]
  \f[B]await\f[R] animation.finished;
  \f[I]// Commit animation state to style attribute\f[R]
  animation.commitStyles();
});
.EE
.PP
This code defines a click handler for the \(lqcommitStyles() with
fill\(rq button.
This also animates the button to move right or left when it is clicked.
As it defines a \f[CR]fill\f[R] it needs to cancel the animation
afterwards.
.PP
Note that \f[CR]commitStyles()\f[R] is called immediately after the
animation is finished.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] commitStylesWithFill = document.querySelector(\(dq.commit\-with\-fill\(dq);
\f[B]let\f[R] offset2 = 0;

commitStylesWithFill.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, \f[B]async\f[R] (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Start the animation\f[R]
  offset2 = 100 \- offset2;
  \f[B]const\f[R] animation = commitStylesWithFill.animate(
    { transform: \(gatranslate(${offset2}px)\(ga },
    { duration: 500, fill: \(dqforwards\(dq },
  );

  \f[I]// Wait for the animation to finish\f[R]
  \f[B]await\f[R] animation.finished;
  \f[I]// Commit animation state to style attribute\f[R]
  animation.commitStyles();
  \f[I]// Cancel the animation\f[R]
  animation.cancel();
});
.EE
.PP
This code defines a click handler for the \(lqNo commitStyles() or
fill\(rq button.
This also animates the button to move right or left when it is clicked.
It doesn\(cqt define a fill and we don\(cqt cancel the animation.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] noCommitStylesOrFill = document.querySelector(\(dq.no\-commit\-or\-fill\(dq);
\f[B]let\f[R] offset3 = 0;

noCommitStylesOrFill.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, \f[B]async\f[R] (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Start the animation\f[R]
  offset3 = 100 \- offset3;
  \f[B]const\f[R] animation = noCommitStylesOrFill.animate(
    { transform: \(gatranslate(${offset3}px)\(ga },
    { duration: 500 },
  );
});
.EE
.SS Result
Click the buttons to animate them.
Note that the first button will \(lqjump\(rq at the end of the animation
if the current browser still requires \f[CR]fill\f[R] for styles to be
committed after the end of the animation.
The \(lqNo commitStyles() or fill\(rq button always jumps at the end,
because the final state is not saved.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
Web Animations API
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Animation\f[R] for other methods and properties you can use to
control web page animation.
